'''Aspedamite''' is a very rare mineral, one of two natural [[heteropolyniobate]]s.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mindat.org/min-42356.html |title=Aspedamite: Aspedamite mineral information and data |website=Mindat.org |accessdate=2016-03-04}}</ref> Its chemical formula (one of the possible formulas) is complex and shows the presence of essential vacancies: []<sub>12</sub>(Fe<sup>3+</sup><sub>2</sub>Fe<sup>2+</sup>)Nb<sub>4</sub>(ThNb<sub>9</sub>Fe<sup>3+</sup><sub>2</sub>Ti<sup>4+</sup>O<sub>42</sub>)(H<sub>2</sub>O)<sub>9</sub>(OH)<sub>3</sub>. Its structure (isometric, space group ''Im''3) is the same as of the second known heteropolyniobate - [[menezesite]].<ref>Cooper, M.A., Abdu, Y.A., Ball, N.A., Černý, P., Hawthorne, F.C., and Kristiansen, R., 2012. Aspedamite, Ideally []<sub>12</sub>(Fe<sup>3+</sup>,Fe<sup>2+</sup>)<sub>3</sub>Nb<sub>4</sub>[Th(Nb,Fe<sup>3+</sup>)<sub>12</sub>O<sub>42</sub>]<sub>12</sub>{(H<sub>2</sub>O),(OH)}<sub>12</sub>, a New Heteropolyniobate Mineral Species from the Herrebøkasa Quarry, Aspedammen, Østfold, Southern Norway: Description and Crystal Structure. The Canadian Mineralogist 50, 793-804; DOI: 10.3749/canmin.50.4.793</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mindat.org/min-27607.html |title=Menezesite: Menezesite mineral information and data |website=Mindat.org |accessdate=2016-03-04}}</ref> Aspedamite is somewhat similar to another mineral from Norway, [[peterandresenite]], which is a hexaniobate.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mindat.org/min-43796.html |title=Peterandresenite: Peterandresenite mineral information and data |website=Mindat.org |accessdate=2016-03-04}}</ref>
