'''Émile Bertrand''' (1844–1909) was a [[France|French]] [[mineralogist]], in honour of whom [[bertrandite]] was named by [[Alexis Damour]].<ref name=MI>{{cite web|last=Wilson|first=Wendell E|title=Émile  Bertrand |url=http://www.minrec.org/labels.asp?colid=126|work=Mineralogical Record Biographical Archive|accessdate=8 December 2010}}</ref>  He also gave his name to the ''Bertrand lens'' or [[phase telescope]].

He studied at the [[Mines ParisTech|Ecole des Mines]] in [[Paris]] and was a co-founder of the ''Société française de Minéralogie''.<ref name=MI/> He wrote a book on the application of [[microscopy]] to mineralogical studies, "''De l'Application du microscope à l'étude de la minéralogie''" (1878);<ref>[http://www.worldcat.org/title/de-lapplication-du-microscope-a-letude-de-la-mineralogie/oclc/30855576&referer=brief_results De l'Application du microscope à l'étude de la minéralogie] OCLC WorldCat</ref> published a translation of [[Ernst Mach]]'s work on the history of mechanics, "''La mécanique: exposé historique et critique de son développement''" (1904);<ref>[https://books.google.com/books/about/La_m%C3%A9canique.html?id=7RT-mQEACAAJ La mécanique] Google Books</ref> and is credited with the design of a [[refractometer]].<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=2UX1CAAAQBAJ&pg=PA43&lpg=PA43&dq=Bertrand+refractometer&source=bl&ots=mj_mYRNinA&sig=l1yiIe1OKXHjgoVCbWZT0MtmO-8&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwj2w6S-5-7JAhUC8CYKHaksCNUQ6AEIIDAB#v=onepage&q=Bertrand%20refractometer&f=false Dictionary of Gems and Gemology] by Mohsen Manutchehr-Danai</ref>

